# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: xslt-stylesheet
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] A **markup language** is a text-encoding system which specifies the structure and formatting of a document and potentially the relationships among its parts.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] Markup can control the display of a document or enrich its content to facilitate automated processing.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] A markup language is a set of rules governing what markup information may be included in a document and how it is combined with the content of the document in a way to facilitate use by humans and computer programs.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] The idea and terminology evolved from the marking up of paper manuscripts (e.g., with revision instructions by editors), traditionally written with a red pen or blue pencil on authors' manuscripts.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] Older markup languages, which typically focus on typesetting and presentation, include troff, TeX, and LaTeX.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] Scribe and most modern markup languages, such as XML, identify document components (for example headings, paragraphs, and tables), with the expectation that technology, such as stylesheets, will be used to apply formatting or other processing.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] Some markup languages, such as the widely used HTML, have pre-defined presentation semantics, meaning that their specifications prescribe some aspects of how to present the structured data on particular media.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] HTML, like DocBook, Open eBook, JATS, and many others, are based on the markup metalanguages XML and SGML.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] That is, SGML and XML allow designers to specify particular schemas, which determine which elements, attributes, and other features are permitted, and where.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] A key characteristic of most markup languages is that they allow combining markup with content such as text and pictures.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] For example, if a few words in a sentence need to be emphasized, or identified as a proper name, defined term, or another special item, the markup may be inserted between the characters of the sentence.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] The word *markup* is derived from the traditional publishing practice of *marking up* a manuscript, which involves adding handwritten annotations in the form of conventional symbolic printer's instructions—in the margins and text of a paper or printed manuscript.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] For centuries, this task was done primarily by skilled typographers known as *markup men* or *markers* who marked up text to indicate what typeface, style, and size should be applied to each part, and then passed the manuscript to others for typesetting by hand or machine.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] The markup was also commonly applied by editors, proofreaders, publishers, and graphic designers, and by authors themselves, all of whom might also mark things such as corrections and changes.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] There are three general categories of electronic markup, articulated by James Coombs, Allen Renear, and Steven DeRose in 1987, and Tim Bray in 2003.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] Presentational markup is used by traditional word-processing systems.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] Binary codes embedded within document text produce the WYSIWYG ('what you see is what you get') effect.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] Such markup is usually hidden from human users, even authors and editors.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] Such systems use procedural and descriptive markup internally but convert them to present the user with formatted arrangements of type.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] Markup is embedded in text which provides instructions for programs to process the text.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] Well-known examples include troff, TeX, and Markdown.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] Generally, software processes the text sequentially from beginning to end, following the instructions as encountered.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] Such text is often edited with the markup visible and directly manipulated by the author.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] Popular procedural markup systems usually include programming constructs, especially macros, allowing complex sets of instructions to be invoked by a simple name (and perhaps a few parameters).
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] This is much faster, less error-prone, and more maintenance-friendly than re-stating the same or similar instructions in many places.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] Descriptive markup is specifically used to describe parts of the document for what they are, rather than how they should be processed.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] Well-known systems that provide many such labels include LaTeX, HTML, and XML.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] The objective is to decouple the structure of the document from any particular treatment or rendition of it.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] Such markup is often described as *semantic*.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] An example of a descriptive markup is HTML's `<cite>` tag, which is used to label a citation.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] Descriptive markup—sometimes called *logical markup* or *conceptual markup*—encourages authors to write in a way that describes the material conceptually, rather than visually.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] There is considerable overlap and concurrent use of markup types.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] In modern word-processing systems, presentational markup is often saved in descriptive-markup-oriented systems such as XML, and then processed procedurally by implementations.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] The programming in procedural-markup systems, such as TeX, may be used to create higher-level markup systems that are more descriptive in nature, such as LaTeX.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] In recent years, several markup languages have been developed with ease of use as a key goal, and without input from standards organizations, aimed at allowing authors to create formatted text via web browsers, for example in wikis and web forums.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] These are sometimes called lightweight markup languages.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] Markdown, BBCode, and the markup language used by Wikipedia are examples of such languages.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] The first well-known public presentation of markup languages in computer text processing was made by William W.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] Tunnicliffe at a conference in 1967, although he preferred to call it *generic coding.* It can be seen as a response to the emergence of processing programs such as RUNOFF that each used their own control notation, often specific to the target typesetting device.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] In the 1970s, Tunnicliffe led the development of a standard called GenCode for the publishing industry.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] Book designer Stanley Rice published speculation along similar lines in 1970.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] Brian Reid, in his 1980 dissertation at Carnegie Mellon University, developed a theory and working implementation of descriptive markup in actual use.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] However, IBM researcher Charles Goldfarb is more commonly considered the inventor of markup languages.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] Goldfarb developed the basic idea while working on a primitive document management system intended for law firms in 1969, and helped invent IBM's Generalized Markup Language (GML) later that same year.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] GML was first publicly disclosed in 1973.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] In 1975, Goldfarb moved from Cambridge, Massachusetts to Silicon Valley and became a product planner at the IBM Almaden Research Center.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] There, he convinced IBM's executives to deploy GML commercially in 1978 as part of IBM's Document Composition Facility product, and it was widely used in business within a few years.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] Standard Generalized Markup Language (SGML), the first standard descriptive markup language, was based on both GML and GenCode.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] It was the result of an International Organization for Standardization (ISO) committee that was first chaired by Tunnicliffe, and which Goldfarb also worked on beginning in 1974.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] Goldfarb eventually became chair of the committee.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] SGML was first released by ISO as the ISO 8879 standard in October 1986.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] Some early examples of computer markup languages available outside the publishing industry can be found in typesetting tools on Unix systems such as troff and nroff.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] In these systems, formatting commands were inserted into the document text so that typesetting software could format the text according to the editor's specifications.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] It was a trial and error iterative process to correctly print a document.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] The availability of WYSIWYG publishing software supplanted much use of these languages among casual users, though professional publishing work still uses markup to specify the non-visual structure of texts, and WYSIWYG editors now usually save documents in a markup-language-based format.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] Another major publishing standard is TeX, created and refined by Donald Knuth in the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] TeX concentrated on the detailed layout of text and font descriptions to typeset mathematical books.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] This required Knuth to spend considerable time investigating the art of typesetting.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] TeX is mainly used in academia, where it is a *de facto* standard in many scientific disciplines.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] A TeX macro package known as LaTeX provides a descriptive markup system on top of TeX, and is widely used both among the scientific community and the publishing industry.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] The first language to make a clear distinction between structure and presentation was Scribe, developed by Brian Reid and described in his doctoral thesis in 1980.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] Scribe was revolutionary in a number of ways, introducing the idea of styles separated from the marked-up document, and a grammar that controlled the usage of descriptive elements.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] Scribe influenced the development of GML and later SGML, and is a direct ancestor to HTML and LaTeX.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] In the early 1980s, the idea that markup should focus on the structural aspects of a document and leave the visual presentation of that structure to the interpreter led to the creation of SGML.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] The language was developed by a committee chaired by Goldfarb.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] It incorporated ideas from many different sources, including Tunnicliffe's project, GenCode.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] Sharon Adler, Anders Berglund, and James A.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] Marke were also key members of the SGML committee.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] SGML specifies a syntax for including the markup in documents, as well as one for separately describing what tags are allowed, and where (the document type definition (DTD), later known as a schema).
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] This allows authors to create and use any markup they want, selecting tags that make the most sense to them and are named in their own natural languages, while also allowing automated verification.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] Thus, SGML is properly a metalanguage, and many markup languages are derived from it.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] From the late 1980s onward, most substantial new markup languages have been based on SGML, including the Text Encoding Initiative (TEI) guidelines and DocBook.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] SGML was promulgated as the ISO 8879 standard in 1986.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] SGML found wide acceptance and use in fields with very large-scale documentation requirements.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] However, many found it cumbersome and difficult to learn—a side effect of its design attempting to do too much and being too flexible.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] For example, SGML made end tags (or start tags, or both) optional in certain contexts, because its developers thought markup would be done manually by overworked support staff who would appreciate saving keystrokes.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] In 1989, computer scientist Tim Berners-Lee wrote a memo proposing an Internet-based hypertext system, then specified HTML and wrote the browser and server software in late 1990.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] The first publicly available description of HTML was a document called "HTML Tags", first mentioned on the Internet by Berners-Lee in late 1991.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] It describes 18 elements comprising the initial, relatively simple design of HTML.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] Except for the hyperlink tag, these were strongly influenced by SGMLguid, an in-house SGML-based documentation format at CERN, and very similar to the sample schema in the SGML standard.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] Eleven of these elements still exist in HTML 4.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] Berners-Lee considered HTML an SGML application.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] The Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) formally defined it as such with the mid-1993 publication of the first proposal for an HTML specification: "Hypertext Markup Language (HTML)" by Berners-Lee and Dan Connolly, which included an SGML DTD to define the grammar.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] These formatting commands were derived from those used by typesetters to manually format documents.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] Steven DeRose argues that HTML's use of descriptive markup (and the influence of SGML in particular) was a major factor in the success of the Web, because of the flexibility and extensibility that it enabled.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] HTML became the main markup language for creating web pages and other information that can be displayed in a web browser and is likely the most used markup language in the world in the 21st century.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] XML (Extensible Markup Language) is a widely used meta markup language.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] It was developed by the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) in a committee created and chaired by Jon Bosak.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] The main purpose of XML was to simplify SGML by focusing on a particular use case—documents on the Internet.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] XML remains a metalanguage like SGML, allowing users to create any tags needed (hence *extensible*) and then describing those tags and their permitted uses.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] XML adoption was hastened by the fact that every XML document can be written so that it is also an SGML document, allowing existing SGML users and software to switch to XML fairly easily.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] At the same time, XML eliminates many complex features of SGML to simplify implementation environments such as documents and publications.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] It appears to balance simplicity and flexibility, as well as support very robust schema definitions and validation tools, and was rapidly adopted for many uses.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] XML is now widely used for communicating data between applications, serializing program data, for hardware communication protocols, vector graphics, and other uses besides documents.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] From January 2000 until HTML 5 was released, all W3C recommendations for HTML were based on XML, using XHTML (Extensible HyperText Markup Language).
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] The language specification requires that XHTML documents be *well-formed* XML documents.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] This allows for more rigorous and robust documents, by avoiding many syntax errors which historically led to unwanted browser behavior, while still using document components familiar to HTML users.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] Another difference is that all attribute values in tags must be quoted.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] Both these differences are commonly criticized as verbose but also praised because they make it far easier to detect, localize, and repair errors.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] Finally, all tag and attribute names within the XHTML namespace must be lowercase to be valid.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] HTML, on the other hand, was case-insensitive.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] Many XML-based applications exist, including the Resource Description Framework as RDF/XML, XForms, DocBook, SOAP, and the Web Ontology Language (OWL).
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] For a partial list of these, see list of XML markup languages.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] A common feature of many markup languages is that they intermix the text of a document with markup instructions in the same data stream or file.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] This is not necessary; it is possible to isolate markup from text content, using pointers, offsets, IDs, or other methods to coordinate the two.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] Such *standoff* markup is typical for the internal representations that programs use to work with marked-up documents.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] However, *embedded* or *inline* markup is much more common elsewhere.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] The codes enclosed in angle-brackets `<like this>` are markup instructions (known as *tags*), while the text between these instructions is the actual text of the document.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] The codes `h1`, `p`, and `em` are examples of *semantic* markup, in that they describe the intended purpose or the meaning of the text they include.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] Specifically, `h1` means the enclosed text is a *first-level heading*, `p` means a *paragraph*, and `em` means an *emphasized* word or phrase.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] A program interpreting such structural markup may apply its own rules or styles for presenting the various pieces of text, using different typefaces, boldness, font size, indentation, color, or other styles, as desired.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] For example, a tag such as `h1` might be presented in a large bold sans-serif typeface in an article, or it might be underscored in a monospaced (fixed-width font) document, or it might not change the presentation at all.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] In contrast, the `i` tag in HTML 4 is an example of *presentational* markup, which is generally used to specify a characteristic of the text without specifying the reason for that appearance.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] In this case, the `i` element dictates the use of an italic typeface.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] However, in HTML 5, this element has been repurposed with a more semantic usage: to denote "a span of text in an alternate voice or mood, or otherwise offset from the normal prose in a manner indicating a different quality of text".
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] For example, it is appropriate to use the `i` element to indicate a taxonomic designation or a phrase in another language.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] The change was made to ease the transition from HTML 4 to 5 as smoothly as possible so that deprecated uses of presentational elements would preserve the most likely intended meaning.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] TEI has published extensive guidelines for how to encode texts of interest in the humanities and social sciences, developed through years of international cooperative work.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] These guidelines are used for encoding historical documents, and the works of particular scholars, periods, and genres.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] While the idea of markup language originated with text documents, they are increasingly used in the presentation of other types of information, including playlists, vector graphics, web services, content syndication, and user interfaces.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] Most of these are XML applications because XML is a well-defined and extensible language.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/markup-language] The use of XML has also led to the possibility of combining multiple markup languages into a single profile, like XHTML+SMIL and XHTML+MathML+SVG.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/template-processor] A **template processor** (also known as a **template engine** or **template parser**) is software designed to combine *template*s with data (defined by a data model) to produce resulting documents or programs.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/template-processor] The language that the templates are written in is known as a **template language** or **templating language**.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/template-processor] For purposes of this article, a result document is any kind of formatted output, including documents, web pages, or source code (in source code generation), either in whole or in fragments.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/template-processor] A template engine is ordinarily included as a part of a web template system or application framework, and may be used also as a preprocessor or filter.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/template-processor] Template engines typically include features common to most high-level programming languages, with an emphasis on features for processing plain text.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/template-processor] The templating languages are generally simple substitution-only languages, in contrast to the more sophisticated facilities in full-blown template processors, but may contain some logic.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/template-processor] Simple examples include ‘printf’ print format strings, found in many programming languages, and snippets, found in a number of text editors and source code editors.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/template-processor] In word processors, templates are a common feature, while automatic filling in of the templates is often referred to as mail merge.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/template-processor] An illustrative example of the complementary nature of parsing and templating is the `s` (substitute) command in the sed text processor, originating from search-and-replace in the ed text editor.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/template-processor] For example, `s/(cat|dog)s?/\1s/g` replaces all occurrences of "cat" or "dog" with "cats" or "dogs", without duplicating an existing "s": `(cat|dog)` is the 1st (and only) sub-expression in the regexp, and `\1` in the format string substitutes this into the output.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/template-processor] This may be a relational database, a source file such as XML, an alternate format of flat file database, a spreadsheet or any of other various sources of preformatted data.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/template-processor] Some template processing systems are limited in the types of data that can be used.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/template-processor] Others are designed for maximum flexibility and allow many different types of data.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/template-processor] Additionally some template engines allow additional configuration options.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/template-processor] These may consist of an entire document or a document fragment.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/template-processor] Template processing is used in various contexts for different purposes.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/template-processor] The specific purpose is ordinarily contingent upon the software application or template engine in use.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/template-processor] However, the flexibility of template processing systems often enables unconventional uses for purposes not originally intended by the original designers.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/template-processor] A **template engine** is a specific kind of template processing module that exhibits all of the major features of a modern programming language.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/template-processor] The term *template engine* evolved as a generalized description of programming languages whose primary or exclusive purpose was to process templates and data to output text.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/template-processor] The use of this term is most notably applied to web development using a web template system, and it is also applied to other contexts as well.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/template-processor] Document generation frameworks typically use template processing as the central model for generating documents.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/template-processor] A web template engine processes web templates and source data (typically from a relational database) to produce one or more output web pages or page fragments.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/template-processor] It is ordinarily included as a part of a web template system or application framework.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/template-processor] Currently, template processing software is most frequently used in the context of development for the web.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/template-processor] XSLT is a template processing model designed by W3C.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/template-processor] It is designed primarily for transformations on XML data (into web documents or other output).
[src:xslt-stylesheet/template-processor] Programming languages such as Perl, Python, PHP, Ruby, C#, Java, and Go support template processing either natively, or through add-on libraries and modules.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/template-processor] JavaServer Pages, Active Server Pages, Genshi (for Python), and eRuby are examples of template engines designed specifically for web application development.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/template-processor] Moreover, template processing is sometimes included as a sub-feature of software packages like text editors, IDEs and relational database management systems.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] The design goals of XML emphasize simplicity, generality, and usability across the Internet.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] It is a textual data format with strong support via Unicode for different human languages.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] Although the design of XML focuses on documents, the language is widely used for the representation of arbitrary data structures, such as those used in web services.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] Several schema systems exist to aid in the definition of XML-based languages, while programmers have developed many application programming interfaces (APIs) to aid the processing of XML data.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] The main purpose of XML is serialization, i.e. storing, transmitting, and reconstructing arbitrary data.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] For two disparate systems to exchange information, they need to agree upon a file format.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] It is therefore analogous to a lingua franca for representing information.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] As a markup language, XML labels, categorizes, and structurally organizes information.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] XML tags represent the data structure and contain metadata.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] What is within the tags is data, encoded in the way the XML standard specifies.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] An additional XML schema (XSD) defines the necessary metadata for interpreting and validating XML.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] (This is also referred to as the canonical schema.) An XML document that adheres to basic XML rules is "well-formed"; one that adheres to its schema is "valid".
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] IETF RFC 7303 (which supersedes the older RFC 3023), provides rules for the construction of media types for use in XML message.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] It defines three media types: `application/xml` (`text/xml` is an alias), `application/xml-external-parsed-entity` (`text/xml-external-parsed-entity` is an alias) and `application/xml-dtd`.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] They are used for transmitting raw XML files without exposing their internal semantics.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] RFC 7303 further recommends that XML-based languages be given media types ending in `+xml`, for example, `image/svg+xml` for SVG.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] Further guidelines for the use of XML in a networked context appear in RFC 3470, also known as IETF BCP 70, a document covering many aspects of designing and deploying an XML-based language.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] XML has come into common use for the interchange of data over the Internet.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] Hundreds of document formats using XML syntax have been developed, including RSS, Atom, Office Open XML, OpenDocument, SVG, COLLADA, and XHTML.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] XML also provides the base language for communication protocols such as SOAP and XMPP.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] It is one of the message exchange formats used in the Asynchronous JavaScript and XML (AJAX) programming technique.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] Many industry data standards, such as Health Level 7, OpenTravel Alliance, FpML, MISMO, and the National Information Exchange Model are based on XML and the rich features of the XML schema specification.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] In publishing, Darwin Information Typing Architecture is an XML industry data standard.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] XML is used extensively to underpin various publishing formats.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] One of the applications of XML in science is the representation of operational meteorology information based on IWXXM standards.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] The material in this section is based on the XML Specification.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] This is not an exhaustive list of all the constructs that appear in XML; it provides an introduction to the key constructs most often encountered in day-to-day use.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] character (except Null) may appear in an (1.1) XML document (while some are discouraged).
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] The specification places requirements on what an XML processor must do and not do, but the application is outside its scope.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] Strings of characters that are not markup are content.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] are classified as markup, while the text between them is classified as content.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] In addition, whitespace before and after the outermost element is classified as markup.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] is a logical document component that either begins with a start-tag and ends with a matching end-tag or consists only of an empty-element tag.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] that exists within a start-tag or empty-element tag.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] , where the names of the attributes are "src" and "alt", and their values are "madonna.jpg" and "Madonna" respectively.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] , where the name of the attribute is "number" and its value is "3".
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] An XML attribute can only have a single value and each attribute can appear at most once on each element.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] with some format beyond what XML defines itself.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] that describes some information about themselves.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] XML documents consist entirely of characters from the Unicode repertoire.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] Except for a small number of specifically excluded control characters, any character defined by Unicode may appear within the content of an XML document.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] XML includes facilities for identifying the *encoding* of the Unicode characters that make up the document, and for expressing characters that, for one reason or another, cannot be used directly.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] XML 1.1 extends the set of allowed characters to include all the above, plus the remaining characters in the range U+0001–U+001F.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] At the same time, however, it restricts the use of C0 and C1 control characters other than U+0009 (Horizontal Tab), U+000A (Line Feed), U+000D (Carriage Return), and U+0085 (Next Line) by requiring them to be written in escaped form (for example U+0001 must be written as `&#x01;` or its equivalent).
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] In the case of C1 characters, this restriction is a backwards incompatibility; it was introduced to allow common encoding errors to be detected.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] The code point U+0000 (Null) is the only character that is not permitted in any XML 1.1 document.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] The Unicode character set can be encoded into bytes for storage or transmission in a variety of different ways, called "encodings".
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] Unicode itself defines encodings that cover the entire repertoire; well-known ones include UTF-8 (which the XML standard recommends using, without a BOM) and UTF-16.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] There are many other text encodings that predate Unicode, such as ASCII and various ISO/IEC 8859; their character repertoires are in every case subsets of the Unicode character set.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] XML allows the use of any of the Unicode-defined encodings and any other encodings whose characters also appear in Unicode.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] XML also provides a mechanism whereby an XML processor can reliably, without any prior knowledge, determine which encoding is being used.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] Encodings other than UTF-8 and UTF-16 are not necessarily recognized by every XML parser (and in some cases not even UTF-16, even though the standard mandates it to also be recognized).
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] XML provides *escape* facilities for including characters that are problematic to include directly.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] All permitted Unicode characters may be represented with a *numeric character reference*.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] Consider the Chinese character "中", whose numeric code in Unicode is hexadecimal 4E2D, or decimal 20,013.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] A user whose keyboard offers no method for entering this character could still insert it in an XML document encoded either as `&#20013;` or `&#x4e2d;`.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] Similarly, the string "I <3 Jörg" could be encoded for inclusion in an XML document as `I &lt;3 J&#xF6;rg`.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] `&#0;` is not permitted because the null character is one of the control characters excluded from XML, even when using a numeric character reference.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] An alternative encoding mechanism such as Base64 is needed to represent such characters.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] Comments may appear anywhere in a document outside other markup.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] Comments cannot appear before the XML declaration.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] Comments begin with `<!--` and end with `-->`.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] For compatibility with SGML, the string "--" (double-hyphen) is not allowed inside comments; this means comments cannot be nested.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] The ampersand has no special significance within comments, so entity and character references are not recognized as such, and there is no way to represent characters outside the character set of the document encoding.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] XML 1.0 (Fifth Edition) and XML 1.1 support the direct use of almost any Unicode character in element names, attributes, comments, character data, and processing instructions (other than the ones that have special symbolic meaning in XML itself, such as the less-than sign, "<").
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] The XML specification defines an XML document as a well-formed text, meaning that it satisfies a list of syntax rules provided in the specification.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] The definition of an XML document excludes texts that contain violations of well-formedness rules; they are simply not XML.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] An XML processor that encounters such a violation is required to report such errors and to cease normal processing.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] This policy, occasionally referred to as "draconian error handling", stands in notable contrast to the behavior of programs that process HTML, which are designed to produce a reasonable result even in the presence of severe markup errors.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] XML's policy in this area has been criticized as a violation of Postel's law ("Be conservative in what you send; be liberal in what you accept").
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] The XML specification defines a valid XML document as a well-formed XML document which also conforms to the rules of a Document Type Definition (DTD).
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] In addition to being well formed, an XML document may be *valid*.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] This means that it contains a reference to a Document Type Definition (DTD), and that its elements and attributes are declared in that DTD and follow the grammatical rules for them that the DTD specifies.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] XML processors are classified as *validating* or *non-validating* depending on whether or not they check XML documents for validity.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] A processor that discovers a validity error must be able to report it, but may continue normal processing.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] A DTD is an example of a *schema* or *grammar*.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] Since the initial publication of XML 1.0, there has been substantial work in the area of schema languages for XML.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] Such schema languages typically constrain the set of elements that may be used in a document, which attributes may be applied to them, the order in which they may appear, and the allowable parent/child relationships.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] The oldest schema language for XML is the document type definition (DTD), inherited from SGML.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] DTD technology is still used in many applications because of its ubiquity.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] A newer schema language, described by the W3C as the successor of DTDs, is XML Schema, often referred to by the initialism for XML Schema instances, XSD (XML Schema Definition).
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] XSDs are far more powerful than DTDs in describing XML languages.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] They use a rich datatyping system and allow for more detailed constraints on an XML document's logical structure.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] XSDs also use an XML-based format, which makes it possible to use ordinary XML tools to help process them.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] RELAX NG (Regular Language for XML Next Generation) was initially specified by OASIS and is now a standard (Part 2: *Regular-grammar-based validation* of ISO/IEC 19757 – DSDL).
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] RELAX NG schemas may be written in either an XML based syntax or a more compact non-XML syntax; the two syntaxes are isomorphic and James Clark's conversion tool—Trang—can convert between them without loss of information.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] RELAX NG has a simpler definition and validation framework than XML Schema, making it easier to use and implement.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] It also has the ability to use datatype framework plug-ins; a RELAX NG schema author, for example, can require values in an XML document to conform to definitions in XML Schema Datatypes.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] Schematron is a language for making assertions about the presence or absence of patterns in an XML document.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] Schematron is now a standard (Part 3: *Rule-based validation* of ISO/IEC 19757 – DSDL).
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] DSDL (Document Schema Definition Languages) is a multi-part ISO/IEC standard (ISO/IEC 19757) that brings together a comprehensive set of small schema languages, each targeted at specific problems.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] DSDL includes RELAX NG full and compact syntax, Schematron assertion language, and languages for defining datatypes, character repertoire constraints, renaming and entity expansion, and namespace-based routing of document fragments to different validators.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] DSDL schema languages do not have the vendor support of XML Schemas yet, and are to some extent a grassroots reaction of industrial publishers to the lack of utility of XML Schemas for publishing.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] Some schema languages not only describe the structure of a particular XML format but also offer limited facilities to influence processing of individual XML files that conform to this format.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] DTDs and XSDs both have this ability; they can for instance provide the infoset augmentation facility and attribute defaults.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] RELAX NG and Schematron intentionally do not provide these.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] A cluster of specifications closely related to XML have been developed, starting soon after the initial publication of XML 1.0.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] It is frequently the case that the term "XML" is used to refer to XML together with one or more of these other technologies that have come to be seen as part of the XML core.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] Some other specifications conceived as part of the "XML Core" have failed to find wide adoption, including XInclude, XLink, and XPointer.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] The design goals of XML include, "It shall be easy to write programs which process XML documents." Despite this, the XML specification contains almost no information about how programmers might go about doing such processing.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] The XML Infoset specification provides a vocabulary to refer to the constructs within an XML document, but does not provide any guidance on how to access this information.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] A variety of APIs for accessing XML have been developed and used, and some have been standardized.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] Stream-oriented facilities require less memory and, for certain tasks based on a linear traversal of an XML document, are faster and simpler than other alternatives.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] Tree-traversal and data-binding APIs typically require the use of much more memory, but are often found more convenient for use by programmers; some include declarative retrieval of document components via the use of XPath expressions.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] XSLT is designed for declarative description of XML document transformations, and has been widely implemented both in server-side packages and Web browsers.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] XQuery overlaps XSLT in its functionality, but is designed more for searching of large XML databases.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] Simple API for XML (SAX) is a lexical, event-driven API in which a document is read serially and its contents are reported as callbacks to various methods on a handler object of the user's design.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] SAX is fast and efficient to implement, but difficult to use for extracting information at random from the XML, since it tends to burden the application author with keeping track of what part of the document is being processed.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] It is better suited to situations in which certain types of information are always handled the same way, no matter where they occur in the document.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] Pull parsing treats the document as a series of items read in sequence using the iterator design pattern.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] A pull parser creates an iterator that sequentially visits the various elements, attributes, and data in an XML document.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] Code that uses this iterator can test the current item (to tell, for example, whether it is a start-tag or end-tag, or text), and inspect its attributes (local name, namespace, values of XML attributes, value of text, etc.), and can also move the iterator to the next item.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] The code can thus extract information from the document as it traverses it.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] The recursive-descent approach tends to lend itself to keeping data as typed local variables in the code doing the parsing, while SAX, for instance, typically requires a parser to manually maintain intermediate data within a stack of elements that are parent elements of the element being parsed.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] Pull-parsing code can be more straightforward to understand and maintain than SAX parsing code.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] The Document Object Model (DOM) is an interface that allows for navigation of the entire document as if it were a tree of node objects representing the document's contents.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] A DOM document can be created by a parser, or can be generated manually by users (with limitations).
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] Data types in DOM nodes are abstract; implementations provide their own programming language-specific bindings.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] DOM implementations tend to be memory intensive, as they generally require the entire document to be loaded into memory and constructed as a tree of objects before access is allowed.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] XML data binding is a technique for simplifying development of applications that need to work with XML documents.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] It involves mapping the XML document to a hierarchy of strongly typed objects, rather than using the generic objects created by a DOM parser.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] The resulting code is often easier to read and maintain, and it can help to identify problems at compile time rather than run-time.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] XML data binding is particularly well-suited for applications where the document structure is known and fixed at the time the application is written.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] By creating a strongly typed representation of the XML data, developers can take advantage of modern integrated development environments (IDEs) that provide features like auto-complete, code refactoring, and code highlighting.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] This can make it easier to write correct and efficient code, and reduce the risk of errors and bugs.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] Example data-binding systems include the Java Architecture for XML Binding (JAXB), XML Serialization in .NET Framework, and XML serialization in gSOAP.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] XML has appeared as a first-class data type in other languages.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] The ECMAScript for XML (E4X) extension to the ECMAScript/JavaScript language explicitly defines two specific objects (XML and XMLList) for JavaScript, which support XML document nodes and XML node lists as distinct objects and use a dot-notation specifying parent-child relationships.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] E4X is supported by the Mozilla 2.5+ browsers (though now deprecated) and Adobe Actionscript but has not been widely adopted.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] Similar notations are used in Microsoft's LINQ implementation for Microsoft .NET 3.5 and above, and in Scala (which uses the Java VM).
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] The open-source xmlsh application, which provides a Linux-like shell with special features for XML manipulation, similarly treats XML as a data type, using the <[ ]> notation.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] The Resource Description Framework defines a data type `rdf:XMLLiteral` to hold wrapped, canonical XML.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] Facebook has produced extensions to the PHP and JavaScript languages that add XML to the core syntax in a similar fashion to E4X, namely XHP and JSX respectively.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] XML is an application profile of SGML (ISO 8879).
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] The versatility of SGML for dynamic information display was understood by early digital media publishers in the late 1980s prior to the rise of the Internet.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] By the mid-1990s some practitioners of SGML had gained experience with the then-new World Wide Web, and believed that SGML offered solutions to some of the problems the Web was likely to face as it grew.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] Dan Connolly added SGML to the list of W3C's activities when he joined the staff in 1995; work began in mid-1996 when Sun Microsystems engineer Jon Bosak developed a charter and recruited collaborators.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] Bosak was well-connected in the small community of people who had experience both in SGML and the Web.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] XML was compiled by a working group of eleven members, supported by a (roughly) 150-member Interest Group.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] Technical debate took place on the Interest Group mailing list and issues were resolved by consensus or, when that failed, majority vote of the Working Group.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] A record of design decisions and their rationales was compiled by Michael Sperberg-McQueen on December 4, 1997.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] James Clark served as Technical Lead of the Working Group, notably contributing the empty-element `<empty />` syntax and the name "XML".
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] Other names that had been put forward for consideration included "MAGMA" (Minimal Architecture for Generalized Markup Applications), "SLIM" (Structured Language for Internet Markup) and "MGML" (Minimal Generalized Markup Language).
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] The co-editors of the specification were originally Tim Bray and Michael Sperberg-McQueen.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] Halfway through the project, Bray accepted a consulting engagement with Netscape, provoking vociferous protests from Microsoft.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] Bray was temporarily asked to resign the editorship.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] This led to intense dispute in the Working Group, eventually solved by the appointment of Microsoft's Jean Paoli as a third co-editor.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] The XML Working Group communicated primarily through email and weekly teleconferences.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] The major design decisions were reached in a short burst of intense work between August and November 1996, when the first Working Draft of an XML specification was published.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xml] Further design work continued through 1997, and XML 1.0 became a W3C Recommendation on February 10, 1998.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xpath] The XPath language is based on a tree representation of the XML document, and provides the ability to navigate around the tree, selecting nodes by a variety of criteria.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xpath] In popular use (though not in the official specification), an XPath expression is often referred to simply as "an XPath".
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xpath] Originally motivated by a desire to provide a common syntax and behavior model between XPointer and XSLT, subsets of the XPath query language are used in other W3C specifications such as XML Schema, XForms and the Internationalization Tag Set (ITS).
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xpath] XPath has been adopted by a number of XML processing libraries and tools, many of which also offer CSS Selectors, another W3C standard, as a simpler alternative to XPath.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xpath] There are several versions of XPath in use.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xpath] However, XPath 1.0 is still the version that is most widely available.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xpath] The most important kind of expression in XPath is a *location path*.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xpath] A location path consists of a sequence of *location steps*.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xpath] An XPath expression is evaluated with respect to a *context node*.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xpath] An Axis Specifier such as 'child' or 'descendant' specifies the direction to navigate from the context node.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xpath] The node test and the predicate are used to filter the nodes specified by the axis specifier: For example, the node test 'A' requires that all nodes navigated to must have label 'A'.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xpath] A predicate can be used to specify that the selected nodes have certain properties, which are specified by XPath expressions themselves.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xpath] The XPath syntax comes in two flavors: the *abbreviated syntax*, is more compact and allows XPaths to be written and read easily using intuitive and, in many cases, familiar characters and constructs.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xpath] The *full syntax* is more verbose, but allows for more options to be specified, and is more descriptive if read carefully.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xpath] The compact notation allows many defaults and abbreviations for common cases.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xpath] that selects C elements that are children of B elements that are children of the A element that forms the outermost element of the XML document.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xpath] The XPath syntax is designed to mimic URI (Uniform Resource Identifier) and Unix-style file path syntax.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xpath] More complex expressions can be constructed by specifying an axis other than the default 'child' axis, a node test other than a simple name, or predicates, which can be written in square brackets after any step.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xpath] selects the first child ('`*[1]`'), whatever its name, of every B element that itself is a child or other, deeper descendant ('`//`') of an A element that is a child of the current context node (the expression does not begin with a '`/`').
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xpath] The predicate `[1]` binds more tightly than the `/` operator.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xpath] To select the first node selected by the expression `A//B/*`, write `(A//B/*)[1]`.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xpath] Note also, index values in XPath predicates (technically, 'proximity positions' of XPath node sets) start from 1, not 0 as common in languages like C and Java.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xpath] Here, in each step of the XPath, the **axis** (e.g.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xpath] `child` or `descendant-or-self`) is explicitly specified, followed by `::` and then the **node test**, such as `A` or `node()` in the examples above.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xpath] Axis specifiers indicate navigation direction within the tree representation of the XML document.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xpath] As an example of using the **attribute** axis in abbreviated syntax, `//a/@href` selects the attribute called `href` in `a` elements anywhere in the document tree.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xpath] The expression **.** (an abbreviation for **self::node()**) is most commonly used within a predicate to refer to the currently selected node.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xpath] For example, `h3[.='See also']` selects an element called `h3` in the current context, whose text content is `See also`.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xpath] Node tests may consist of specific node names or more general expressions.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xpath] In the case of an XML document in which the namespace prefix `gs` has been defined, `//gs:enquiry` will find all the `enquiry` elements in that namespace, and `//gs:*` will find all elements, regardless of local name, in that namespace.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xpath] Predicates, written as expressions in square brackets, can be used to filter a node-set according to some condition.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xpath] For example, `a` returns a node-set (all the `a` elements which are children of the context node), and `a[@href='help.php']` keeps only those elements having an `href` attribute with the value `help.php`.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xpath] There is no limit to the number of predicates in a step, and they need not be confined to the last step in an XPath.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xpath] Paths specified in predicates begin at the context of the current step (i.e. that of the immediately preceding node test) and do not alter that context.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xpath] All predicates must be satisfied for a match to occur.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xpath] When the value of the predicate is numeric, it is syntactic-sugar for comparing against the node's position in the node-set (as given by the function `position()`).
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xpath] So `p[1]` is shorthand for `p[position()=1]` and selects the first `p` element child, while `p[last()]` is shorthand for `p[position()=last()]` and selects the last `p` child of the context node.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xpath] In other cases, the value of the predicate is automatically converted to a Boolean.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xpath] When the predicate evaluates to a node-set, the result is true when the node-set is non-empty.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xpath] Thus `p[@x]` selects those `p` elements that have an attribute named `x`.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xpath] The reference to an attribute of the top-level element in the first predicate affects neither the context of other predicates nor that of the location step itself.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xpath] Predicate order is significant if predicates test the position of a node.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xpath] Each predicate takes a node-set returns a (potentially) smaller node-set.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xpath] So `a[1][@href='help.php']` will find a match only if the first `a` child of the context node satisfies the condition `@href='help.php'`, while `a[@href='help.php'][1]` will find the first `a` child that satisfies this condition.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xpath] XPath 1.0 defines four data types: node-sets (sets of nodes with no intrinsic order), strings, numbers and Booleans.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xpath] Some of the more commonly useful functions are detailed below.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xpath] returns a number representing the position of this node in the sequence of nodes currently being processed (for example, the nodes selected by an xsl:for-each instruction in XSLT).
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xpath] returns the number of nodes in the node-set supplied as its argument.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xpath] converts any of the four XPath data types into a string according to built-in rules.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xpath] If the value of the argument is a node-set, the function returns the string-value of the first node in document order, ignoring any further nodes.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xpath] is removed and any sequences of whitespace characters are replaced by a single space.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xpath] formatted, which could make further string processing unreliable.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xpath] converts the string values of all the nodes found by the XPath argument into numbers, according to the built-in casting rules, then returns the sum of these numbers.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xpath] Expressions can be created inside predicates using the operators: `=, !=, <=, <, >=` and `>`.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xpath] Boolean expressions may be combined with brackets `()` and the Boolean operators `and` and `or` as well as the `not()` function described above.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xpath] Numeric calculations can use `*, +, -, div` and `mod`.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xpath] Strings can consist of any Unicode characters.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xpath] `//item[@price > 2*@discount]` selects items whose price attribute is greater than twice the numeric value of their discount attribute.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xpath] Entire node-sets can be combined ('unioned') using the vertical bar character |.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xpath] Node sets that meet one or more of several conditions can be found by combining the conditions inside a predicate with '`or`'.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xpath] `v[x or y] | w[z]` will return a single node-set consisting of all the `v` elements that have `x` or `y` child-elements, as well as all the `w` elements that have `z` child-elements, that were found in the current context.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xpath] selects addresses of all English Wikimedia projects (text of all `edition` elements where `language` attribute is equal to *English*).
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xpath] selects addresses of all Wikipedias (text of all `edition` elements that exist under `project` element with a name attribute of *Wikipedia*).
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xpath] The Java package **`javax.xml.xpath`** has been part of Java standard edition since Java 5 via the Java API for XML Processing.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xpath] Technically this is an XPath API rather than an XPath implementation, and it allows the programmer the ability to select a specific implementation that conforms to the interface.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xpath] XPath is increasingly used to express constraints in schema languages for XML.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xsl] In computing, the term **Extensible Stylesheet Language** (**XSL**) is used to refer to a family of languages used to transform and render XML documents (e.g., XSL is used to determine how to display a XML document as a webpage).
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xsl] XML Path Language (XPath): a non-XML language used by XSLT, and also available for use in non-XSLT contexts, for addressing the parts of an XML document.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xsl] XSL began as an attempt to bring the functionality of DSSSL, particularly in the area of print and high-end typesetting, to XML.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xsl] In response to a submission from Arbortext, Inso, and Microsoft, a W3C working group on *XSL* started operating in December 1997, with Sharon Adler and Steve Zilles as co-chairs, with James Clark acting as editor (and unofficially as chief designer), and Chris Lilley as the W3C staff contact.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xsl] The group released a first public Working Draft on 18 August 1998.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xsl] XSLT and XPath became W3C Recommendations on 16 November 1999 and XSL-FO reached Recommendation status on 15 October 2001.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xsl] The original version of XSLT (1.0) was published in November 1999, and was widely implemented.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xsl] These products all have a high level of conformance to the specification, though they also offer proprietary vendor extensions, and some of them omit support for optional features such as disable-output-escaping.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xsl] Subsequent versions of XSLT include XSLT 2.0 (January 2007) and XSLT 3.0 (June 2017); there is work in progress on a version 4.0.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xsl] These versions have not been as widely implemented as 1.0: the main implementations in widespread use in 2023 are Saxon (available in various versions for different platforms, including web browsers), and Altova's RaptorXML.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xsl] XML Path Language (XPath), itself part of the XSL family, functions within XSLT as a means of navigating an XML document.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xsl] Another W3C project, XQuery, aims to provide similar capabilities for querying XML documents using XPath.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xslt] XSLT 3.0 implementations support Java, .NET, C/C++, Python, PHP and NodeJS.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xslt] An XSLT 3.0 JavaScript library can also be hosted within the web browser.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xslt] Modern web browsers also include native support for XSLT 1.0.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xslt] XSLT has become obsolete in the browser due to better technologies.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xslt] Google Chrome will remove its XSLT implementation to make the browser more secure.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xslt] The XSLT document transformation specifies how to transform an XML document into new document (usually XML, but other formats, such as plain text are supported).
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xslt] Typically, input documents are XML files, but anything from which the processor can build an XQuery and XPath Data Model can be used, such as relational database tables or geographical information systems.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xslt] While XSLT was originally designed as a special-purpose language for XML transformation, the language is Turing-complete, making it theoretically capable of arbitrary computations.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xslt] XSLT is influenced by functional languages, and by text-based pattern matching languages like SNOBOL and AWK.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xslt] Its most direct predecessor is DSSSL, which did for SGML what XSLT does for XML.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xslt] The XSLT processor takes one or more XML source documents, plus one or more XSLT stylesheets, and processes them to produce one or multiple output documents.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xslt] In contrast to widely implemented imperative programming languages like C, XSLT is declarative.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xslt] The basic processing paradigm is pattern matching.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xslt] First, assuming a stylesheet has already been read and prepared, the processor builds a source tree from the input XML document.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xslt] It then processes the source tree's root node, finds the best-matching template for that node in the stylesheet, and evaluates the template's contents.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xslt] Instructions in each template generally direct the processor to either create nodes in the result tree, or to process more nodes in the source tree in the same way as the root node.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xslt] Finally the result tree is serialized as XML or HTML text.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xslt] XSLT uses XPath to identify subsets of the source document tree and perform calculations.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xslt] XPath also provides a range of functions, which XSLT itself further augments.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xslt] XSLT 1.0 uses XPath 1.0, while XSLT 2.0 uses XPath 2.0.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xslt] XSLT 3.0 will work with either XPath 3.0 or 3.1.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xslt] In the case of 1.0 and 2.0, the XSLT and XPath specifications were published on the same date.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xslt] With 3.0, however, they were no longer synchronized; XPath 3.0 became a Recommendation in April 2014, followed by XPath 3.1 in February 2017; XSLT 3.0 followed in June 2017.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xslt] XSLT functionalities overlap with those of XQuery, which was initially conceived as a query language for large collections of XML documents.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xslt] The XSLT 2.0 and XQuery 1.0 standards were developed by separate working groups within W3C, working together to ensure a common approach where appropriate.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xslt] They share the same data model, type system, and function library, and both include XPath 2.0 as a sublanguage.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xslt] The two languages, however, are rooted in different traditions and serve the needs of different communities.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xslt] XSLT was primarily conceived as a stylesheet language whose primary goal was to render XML for the human reader on screen, on the web (as a web template language), or on paper.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xslt] XQuery was primarily conceived as a database query language in the tradition of SQL.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xslt] Because the two languages originate in different communities, XSLT is stronger in its handling of narrative documents with more flexible structure, while XQuery is stronger in its data handling, for example when performing relational joins.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xslt] The `<output>` element can optionally take the attribute `media-type`, which allows one to set the media type (or MIME type) for the resulting output, for example: `<xsl:output output="xml" media-type="application/xml"/>`.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xslt] The XSLT 1.0 recommendation recommends the more general attribute types `text/xml` and `application/xml` since for a long time there was no registered media type for XSLT.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xslt] During this time `text/xsl` became the de facto standard.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xslt] In XSLT 1.0 it was not specified how the `media-type` values should be used.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xslt] With the release of the XSLT 2.0, the W3C recommended in 2007 the registration of the MIME media type `application/xslt+xml` and it was later registered with the Internet Assigned Numbers Authority.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xslt] Pre-1.0 working drafts of XSLT used `text/xsl` in their embedding examples, and this type was implemented and continued to be promoted by Microsoft in Internet Explorer and MSXML circa 2012.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xslt] It is also widely recognized in the `xml-stylesheet` processing instruction by other browsers.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xslt] In practice, therefore, users wanting to control transformation in the browser using this processing instruction were obliged to use this unregistered media type.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xslt] This XHTML generates the output below when rendered in a web browser.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xslt] In order for a web browser to be able to apply an XSL transformation to an XML document on display, an XML stylesheet processing instruction can be inserted into XML.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xslt] In this example, `text/xsl` is technically incorrect according to the W3C specifications (which say the type should be `application/xslt+xml`), but it is the only media type that is widely supported across browsers as of 2009, and the situation is unchanged in 2021.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xslt] Most early XSLT processors were interpreters.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xslt] More recently, code generation is increasingly common, using portable intermediate languages (such as Java bytecode or .NET Common Intermediate Language) as the target.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xslt] However, even the interpretive products generally offer separate analysis and execution phases, allowing an optimized expression tree to be created in memory and reused to perform multiple transformations.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xslt] This gives substantial performance benefits in online publishing applications, where the same transformation is applied many times per second to different source documents.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xslt] This separation is reflected in the design of XSLT processing APIs (such as JAXP).
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xslt] Early XSLT processors had very few optimizations.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xslt] Stylesheet documents were read into Document Object Models and the processor would act on them directly.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xslt] Many processors also use tree representations that are significantly more efficient (in both space and time) than general-purpose DOM implementations.
[src:xslt-stylesheet/xslt] In June 2014, Debbie Lockett and Michael Kay introduced an open-source benchmarking framework for XSLT processors called XT-Speedo.
